# BidPazar – Lean Engineering Rules

## Tech Stack & Runtime
- Next.js 15 (App Router) + custom Node.js server (`server.js`)
- PostgreSQL + Prisma ORM
- Real-time: Socket.IO (chat, bidding) + LiveKit (media)
- Auth: Custom JWT (jose) + NextAuth.js hybrid
- UI: TailwindCSS + CSS variables, TypeScript, Turkish interface
- Start apps with `npm run dev` (local) or `npm start` (prod). Do not use `next dev` directly.

## Environment Variables
- Use Next.js built-in `.env*` loading. Access via `process.env` only. Do not create custom `env.ts` wrappers.
- Client variables must be prefixed with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`. Never expose secrets with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`.
- Typical server-only: `DATABASE_URL`, `JWT_SECRET`, `SMS_PASSWORD`, `LIVEKIT_API_SECRET`.
- Typical client: `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL`, `NEXT_PUBLIC_SOCKET_URL`, `NEXT_PUBLIC_LIVEKIT_URL`.
- Commit `.env.example`. Keep other `.env*` files in `.gitignore`. Use environment-specific files.
- Use env flags for debug (e.g., `DEBUG_AUTH`, `DEBUG_MESSAGES`, `DEBUG_CHAT`).

## Authentication
- JWT with `jose` (Edge-compatible), 7-day sessions. Token stored in localStorage + HTTP cookies.
- Validate server-side in middleware (cookies/Authorization). Auto-refresh with rate limiting.
- On app version mismatch, log out and clear auth.
- Cookie settings: `path=/; max-age=604800`. Clean up on logout.
- Client: `AuthProvider` + `useAuth()`; protected requests use `withAuthHeader()`; token refresh via `validateToken()`.

## API Design (App Router)
- Route Handlers live under `src/app/api/`.
- Collections: `src/app/api/[resource]/route.ts`; Items: `src/app/api/[resource]/[id]/route.ts`.
- Handle multiple methods per route file; return consistent JSON.
- Validate all inputs with Zod. Always provide loading states and error handling in clients.
- Error format: `{ error: string, details?: any }`. Success: `{ data: any, meta?: any }`.
- Respond 405 for unsupported methods.

```typescript
// Example: src/app/api/users/route.ts
import { NextRequest } from "next/server";
export async function GET(_req: NextRequest) { return Response.json({ data: [] }); }
export async function POST(req: NextRequest) {
  const body = await req.json();
  return Response.json({ data: body }, { status: 201 });
}
```

## Middleware (Edge-friendly)
- Default to Edge Runtime. Skip WebSocket/Socket.IO requests.
- Public paths are grouped (static, auth, pages, api). Keep a single matcher without capturing groups.
- Extract tokens from cookies and headers. Use a single redirect helper for unauthenticated cases.
- Control logging via env (e.g., `DEBUG_NOTIFICATIONS`).

## Real-time: LiveKit + Socket.IO
- LiveKit for audio/video: generate tokens server-side using `livekit-server-sdk`. Never expose API secret to client.
- Client uses `@livekit/components-react`. Configure granular publish/subscribe permissions.
- Socket.IO for chat/bidding/timers. Namespaces/rooms: `stream:{id}`, `user:{id}`, `conversation:{id}`.
- Persist messages/bids via API before emitting over sockets.
- Make the Socket.IO instance available globally in API routes via `global.socketIO`.
- Authenticate socket handshakes (token & user), handle join/leave, and clean up on disconnect.

## Database/Prisma
- Define descriptive migrations, be careful with cascade deletes.
- Use `select` to fetch only required fields.

## Styling & UX
- Use CSS variables: `var(--background)`, `var(--foreground)`, `var(--accent)`, etc.
- Support dark/light themes; mobile-first responsive design.
- Prefer utility classes; provide premium UI classes like `.premium-button`, `.premium-input`.

## Security
- Never expose secrets in client code.
- Validate tokens on both client and server; CSRF-safe fetches; secure cookies in production.
- Enforce CORS appropriately.
- Handle token expiration and app version changes gracefully.

## File/Folder Pointers
- `server.js`: Custom Node + Socket.IO integration.
- `src/app/api/*`: Route Handlers (RESTful, validated, authenticated where required).
- `src/lib/*`: `auth.ts`, `frontend-auth.ts`, `livekit.ts`, `api-middleware.ts`, `prisma.ts`.
- `src/components/*`: Reusable UI; `components/AuthProvider.tsx` for global auth state.
- `src/app/live-streams/*`: Streaming pages, components, hooks, styles.

## Common Patterns
- Loading state: `const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false)`.
- Try/catch for API calls with user-friendly errors.
- Forms: `react-hook-form` + Zod.
- Protected API calls: `fetch(url, withAuthHeader())`.

## Avoid
- Creating custom env wrappers. Use `process.env` directly.
- Using `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` for secrets.
- Monolithic API files. Keep endpoints modular under App Router.
- Missing validation or inconsistent response shapes.
- Unhandled HTTP methods (always return 405).
- Direct DB queries in React components (use API routes).
- Overly complex middleware or blocking WebSocket/Socket.IO requests.
- Inline styles or arbitrary hard-coded strings; avoid `any` types.
- Console logs in production (guard with env or remove).
